nodes.body: Nice.
Random thought: should these utilities be gathered inside a single `Utils` top-level dir? Something like `ImportGraph` would also fit there imho.
What's the situation here? I think it looks alright I agree with Johan that this should be moved to a `Utils` directory.

Sorry, this has dropped off my queue. I'll add `please-adopt`. Please feel free to push anything to this branch!

It would be lovely to hook this up to a bot that regularly posts the output somewhere.
Ok I agree with the previous comments about making a Utils directory so I have done that. I have also updated the code to allow specifying a specific hash.

Good question. The Utils folder I created for this is a different one from `Mathlib/Util` - this new folder is outside the `Mathlib` directory. It basically is in the same state as `Shake` and `Cache`, so if those aren't causing problems, I guess this won't either? I was definitely planning to follow up with a PR putting `Shake` and `Cache` alongside `LongestPole`.

But I see that Mario has provided some additional advice in that thread, so let me consider it more carefully.
From discussing on Zulip, it seems that making a new `LongestPole` is currently the preferred way of doing.

After reading the thread more carefully it seems like what Mario is saying is that all of these things should look in `lakefile.lean` the same way that checkYaml does. I definitely agree they should all be in the same directory. Whether that directory is `scripts/` or this new `Utils/`, I am ambivalent, but I lean toward letting `scripts/` be for non-lean, and `Utils/` be for lean.

> From discussing on Zulip, it seems that making a new `LongestPole` is currently the preferred way of doing.

Wait, what exactly do you mean - a new `LongestPole` file? directory? repo? Whatever it is feel free to reorganize this PR to whatever seems sensible/start a new PR if you want to keep the organizational issue separate.
Executable! I meant executable. I think you just need to revert your `move to utils` commit.
Ok I have returned this to the same directory format and lakefile structure as Shake, if we want to change this in a later PR we can do so.

Hmm, I just noticed that while this file gets its instruction counts from `http://speed.lean-fro.org`, it gets the importgraph from the environment, so the ability to speed-test other commits is currently bugged. I am going to put that part in another PR.

If this is a generic tool, not necessarily depending on mathlib, you could consider PRing it to [import-graph](https://github.com/leanprover-community/import-graph), which already holds tools like `lake exe graph` and `#find_home` which were previously in Mathlib.

> If this is a generic tool, not necessarily depending on mathlib, you could consider PRing it to [import-graph](https://github.com/leanprover-community/import-graph), which already holds tools like `lake exe graph` and `#find_home` which were previously in Mathlib.

This seems like a very good suggestion to me, because this seems pretty clearly related to the functionality of import-graph - I like it better than any of the location proposals so far.

You probably want to include whitespaces between the sentences, e.g., after the '.' at the end of each sentence.
Done.

I don't find the speedcenter ids very helpful. Why do you print those? AFAIU the git hash is all we need.

Also, instead of printing the plain id, I would print something like per row:

`lake exe pole --hash  30d39f9`

Which (assuming the --hash command exists) is directly executable. Currently I have to (a) git diff the current patch, (b) checkout the proposed hash, (c) patch -p1 < diff to get any output.

I believe it is sufficient to print the first eight characters of the hash.

Good point. The ids were helpful while I was debugging.

Unfortunately a `--hash` command won't work: it's better to just checkout the hash and run `lake exe pole` there.
I've updated the advice text here. Could you take another look, please?
I added one more comment, otherwise this looks great.

You probably already want to break after "assuming" and then probably once more after "over" to not be double-broken in a 80 column terminal. Alternatively, you may just not break the sentences at all.
Done.
What does the string "e7b27246-a3e6-496a-b552-ff4b45c7236e" signify? Should it be hard-coded? I'm fine with that, but may add a short comment explaining this.
Good point. It is the `repo_id` for Mathlib.

Sorry, I keep on changing my mind as I discover more about Lean executables: Could you rename the file to `scripts/longestPole.lean` and change the lakefile to use `srcDir` rather than `root`?
```suggestion
  srcDir := "scripts"
```

Again, I am in favor of all the executables being located in the same place and being declared in the same way. This sounds fine to me, but I think it would be best to do this for all the executables simultaneously in one PR to make sure they are all in harmony with each other.
That's already the case, see `checkYaml`. `Cache` is special-cased because it's multi-file and Lake currently has a weird one-file restriction on executables
Right, and `Shake` is currently the way `LongestPole` is now. I stand by saying that these organizational issues should be dealt with in a separate PR, where they can be reviewed separately.
I split this into multiple files, so now I think this is moot
What is the use of these two structures? Is this to get the Lean structures aligned with some JSON data structure?
Yes. See for example this API output http://speed.lean-fro.org/mathlib4/api/run/e7b27246-a3e6-496a-b552-ff4b45c7236e?hash=9aded8e01ba2ac52c5e6864d9847cf26c6aaa015
Can you put these all in a `SpeedCenterApi` namespace to it this clear that these follow that json format, and should be kept in sync with the API? You could then drop the `SpeedCenter` prefices.

Is there a reason to prefer `.getD 0` over `.get!`? These lines become quite long... I could imagine even having a `.find!`.

(Also elsewhere.)
Seems like some of these `find?` can be replaced by `find!` and some can't (`instructions` doesn't have all the names that the other `nameMap`s have). I'll replace the ones I can.
I spotted a PANIC in a recent run of the code, so I must have made a mistake with this somewhere
side remark: I believe `(cumulative.find? n).getD 0` can be golfed to `cumulative.findD n 0`

Are these not yet available in some lower level lib? I'm fine with having them here for now...
What is the risk that others will try to import this file and get a name conflict?
Risk of this being imported seems minimal, since the point of this file is just to be the `Main` file for the executable. I'll put a todo note to move them.
Hmm, perhaps we should have been more worried about a _lack_ of name conflict: I am now observing that a `String.leftpad` already exists. Unfortunately `rightpad` does not.

Ok I have now

* deleted `leftPad` in favor of the preexisting `leftpad`
* kept the existing `leftpad` type signature, but added the default argument whitespace.
* moved/renamed `rightPad` to match.
* Commented that the Std API should be updated so that the definitions can be analogous
Why the 3 here?
Not sure - perhaps because it is the third layer beyond the two layers of `Source` tags? I am not sure that it's helpful so I removed it.
I think this should be called `CommitSource` or similar, since it corresponds to `type: "COMMIT"`
@BoltonBailey, did you intend to apply this change?
Yes, and I did so.
Can you extract this to some `Float.toStringDecimals (f : Float) (digits : Nat)` helper function?

```suggestion
structure SpeedCenterAPI.Source1 where
```
to respect the naming convention
https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/8361#discussion_r1573881736

This and a few other `def`s don't match the naming convention:
```suggestion
def SpeedCenterAPI.runJson (hash : String) (repoId : String := mathlib4RepoId) : IO String :=
```

```suggestion
      m.insert n (instructions.findD n 0 + t)
```

```suggestion
      fun t n' => t + (instructions.findD n' 0)
```

```suggestion
  let to â† match args.flag? "to" with
  | some to => pure <| to.as! ModuleName
  | none => ImportGraph.getCurrentModule -- autodetect the main module from the `lakefile.lean`
```

The downside is that `ImportGraph.getCurrentModule` is a bit hacky by itself. But it's probably reasonable to use it anyways and fix that function if anybody has a better solution.

```suggestion
  unsafe withImportModules #[{module := to}] {} (trustLevel := 1024) fun env => do
```

```suggestion
      let i := instructions.findD n' 0
```

I think `instructions` is the only place where we aren't sure that it contains all the names from `graph` since it comes from a foreign api.

`cumulative`, `total`, `slowest` are all constructed from `graph`, so there it's fine to use `.find!`.
